{:tx/id #hlc "1773931621/0/af86f4b0b23bbbe4de81fe20af03f998"
 :tx/agent "af86f4b0b23bbbe4de81fe20af03f998"
 :tx/provenance :observed
 :tx/rationale "DOG-FOOD ASSESSMENT — Session 026 honest review of using braid as primary workflow tool.\n\nWHAT WORKS WELL:\n(1) braid observe is phenomenal. Low friction, instant capture, content-addressed identity. I used it 20+ times this session and it felt natural every time. The auto-reconciliation (CRB-3) we just added makes it DRAMATICALLY better — seeing related spec elements immediately after observing changed my behavior in real-time.\n(2) braid done + CBV gate is genuinely useful. The acceptance criteria check caught real issues (SPEC-TOPO-TRANSACT needed actual spec elements transacted before it would close). Forces completeness.\n(3) braid topology plan --agents 3 on our own store was a genuine thrill. The self-bootstrap (C7) isn't theoretical — it produces a real, useful agent assignment. S=5.74, p=0.92 is actionable information.\n(4) The Datalog diagnostics I wired in this session immediately paid off. When I queried with the wrong type (string vs keyword), the hint told me exactly what was wrong. Before this fix, I wasted 10+ minutes on a silent 0-result query.\n\nWHAT DOESN'T WORK WELL:\n(1) Task list is nearly unusable at scale. 568 tasks but braid task list shows ~8 due to budget truncation. I had to write raw Datalog queries to find my own tasks. This is the #1 dog-food friction point.\n(2) The query result truncation is aggressive. Even with --budget 50000, agent-mode output gets cut. Had to use --format human --budget 50000 for E2E tests. The budget gate should NEVER truncate when the user explicitly passes a large budget.\n(3) Creating 50+ tasks is tedious. Each braid task create is a separate transaction, ~3s each. Batch creation would save 2+ minutes per planning session.\n(4) spec_relevance_scan is slow on large stores. With 400+ spec elements, every observe call adds ~200ms. Not terrible, but noticeable. Should cache tokenized statements.\n(5) The task dependency system works but has no visualization. I had to draw the dependency graph in ASCII in my commit messages. braid task deps --graph would be valuable.\n(6) braid task show truncates long descriptions. The full BACKGROUND and ACCEPTANCE text is cut off. Need --full flag or braid task show --verbose.\n\nWHAT I WOULD CHANGE:\n(1) braid task list --limit 50 or braid task list --all --no-budget — let me see ALL my tasks.\n(2) braid task batch-create accepting a YAML/EDN file with multiple tasks + deps.\n(3) spec_relevance_scan should be cached per-session (tokenize spec statements once).\n(4) The guidance footer sometimes competes with useful output. For topology plan, the footer was cut but the plan was also cut. Priority should be: command output > footer.\n(5) braid task search <keyword> — I kept writing Datalog queries to find tasks. A search command would be 10x faster.\n\nOVERALL ASSESSMENT: 7.5/10\nThe core loop (observe → harvest → seed) genuinely works. Knowledge survives sessions. The CRB auto-reconciliation is a game-changer — it prevented at least 2 potential duplications in the 30 minutes since I implemented it. The topology system proves the architecture scales to real coordination problems. The main gaps are all UX: task management at scale, query result presentation, batch operations. The kernel is solid; the CLI needs polish."
